 on variety. They are very sweet, containing about 75 percent of sugar when dried.","wiki"),("monks","5","Buddhism originated as a renunciant tradition, practiced by ascetics who had departed from lay life. Out of this tradition grew two kinds of living arrangements for monastics, as detailed in the Mahavagga section of the Vinaya and Varsavastu texts:","wiki"),("roots","5","In vascular plants, the ___ are the organs of a plant that typically lie below the surface of the soil. ___ can also be aerial or aerating, that is, growing up above the ground or especially above water. Furthermore, a stem normally occurring below ground is not exceptional either . Therefore, the root is best defined as the non-leaf, non-nodes bearing parts of the plant's body. There are important internal structural differences between stems and ___.","wiki"),("betel","5","The ___  is a vine of the family Piperaceae, which includes pepper and kava. ___ leaf is mostly consumed in Asia, and elsewhere in the world by some Asian emigrants, as ___ quid or in paan, with Areca nut and/or tobacco.","wiki"),("queen","5","Cycas circinalis, also known as the ___ sago, is a species of cycad known in the wild only from southern India. Cycas circinalis is the only gymnosperm species found among native Sri Lankan flora.","wiki"),("morel","5","Morchella, the true ___s, is a genus of edible sac fungi closely related to anatomically simpler cup fungi in the order Pezizales . These distinctive fungi have a honeycomb appearance due to the network of ridges with pits composing their caps. ___s are prized by gourmet cooks, particularly in French cuisine. Due to difficulties in cultivation, commercial harvesting of wild ___s has become a multimillion-dollar industry in the temperate Northern Hemisphere, in particular North America, Turkey, China, the Himalayas, India, and Pakistan, where these highly prized fungi are found in abundance.","wiki"),("clove","5","The ___ tree is an evergreen that grows up to 8–12 metres  long, and consist of a long calyx that terminates in four spreading sepals, and four unopened petals that form a small central ball.","wiki"),("waxes","5","___ are a diverse class of organic compounds that are lipophilic, malleable solids near ambient temperatures.  They include higher alkanes and lipids, typically with melting points above about 40 °C , melting to give low viscosity liquids. ___ are insoluble in water but soluble in organic, nonpolar solvents.  Natural ___ of different types are produced by plants and animals and occur in petroleum.","wiki"),("kokum","5","___ oil is a seed oil derived from the seeds of the ___ tree .  ___ oil is edible and can also be used for things other than cooking.","wiki"),("kauri","5","___ gum , which is made into crafts such as jewellery. ___ forests once covered much of the North Island of New Zealand, before Māori and European settlers caused deforestation, causing several areas to revert to sand dunes, scrubs, and swamps. Even afterward, ancient ___ fields continued to provide a source for the gum and the remaining forests.","wiki"),("myrrh","5","___ gum is commonly harvested from the species Commiphora ___a. Another commonly used name, Commiphora molmol,","wiki"),("rosin","5","___, also called colophony or Greek pitch , is a solid form of resin obtained from pines and some other plants, mostly conifers, produced by heating fresh liquid resin to vaporize the volatile liquid terpene components. It is semi-transparent and varies in color from yellow to black. At room temperature ___ is brittle, but it melts at stove-top temperature. It chiefly consists of various resin acids, especially abietic acid.","wiki"),("latex","5","___ is a stable dispersion  of polymer microparticles in an aqueous medium. It is found in nature, but synthetic ___es can be made by polymerizing a monomer such as styrene that has been emulsified with surfactants.","wiki"),("ferns","5","A fern  and eusporangiate ___, the latter group including horset